history.content:
In the situation you describe, I agree that changing discussion section would be unwise (specifically, because you are so close to the front of the lecture waitlist).  That being said, discussions 112 and 115 would make an ok bet assuming a fair # of students on the waitlist aren't declared cs/eecs and you are.

Regarding the question you ask: I'm not completely sure at this point.

children.subject: That wasn't actually true in telebears. In either system, you are either enrolled in the class or not and to be enrolled in the class you need to be enrolled in both. It's like you can't be in the back seat of a car unless you are both in the back seat and in the car; you can't be in the back seat without also being in the car.

I see, makes sense.

In that case, discussion waitlist position (which we can't see) will be far more informative than lecture waitlist position, since direct enrolment in particular discussion => enrolment in lecture and waitlist in particular discussion => waitlist for lecture (even if direct enrolment to lecture is possible just by changing sections!). Correct me if I'm wrong.

My last question will be: When can we know of updates on the 70 remaining seats for CS 170?
As soon as I know, you'll know and I don't know how long it will be until I know. I'm hoping it will be by sometime next week.
If the seats are released next week, just to confirm, that means that processing off the waitlist won't involve any type of priority, right?

Thank you for the response. 

So, the waitlists for the discussion and lecture are processed separately, i.e. I can be enrolled in the lecture but waitlisted for the discussion (just like in TeleBears) ?

history.content:
After reading a lot of posts, I know the following:

1.) I cannot see my position in the discussion section.
2.) There is no way I can change my particular section (since I'm waitlisted) without dropping from my waitlist position in the *lecture*.

Situation: I'm currently at < 10 position on the waitlist for CS 170, a good chance of getting in. However, if I try to switch section, implying I drop the class and re-add myself to a different section, it is highly unlikely I'll get in and will get a way worse waitlist number. Hence, the risk is higher for me, I shouldn't even try it (or should I?).

Question: When the last 70 seats will be released (TA hiring complete), will new discussions sections will be formed or the same discussion sections be expanded?

Thank you for any advise or suggestion!
